5.11 Exercise – Problem 7

For your retail time series (from Exercise 8 in Section 2.10):

a. Create a training dataset consisting of observations before 2011

set.seed(1)
aus_retail <- aus_retail
myseries <- aus_retail %>%
  filter(`Series ID` == sample(aus_retail$`Series ID`, 1))

myseries_train <- myseries %>%
  filter(year(Month) < 2011)

b. Check that your data have been split appropriately by producing the following plot.

autoplot(myseries, Turnover) +
  autolayer(myseries_train, Turnover, colour = "red")

c. Fit a seasonal naïve model using SNAIVE() applied to your training data (myseries_train).

fit <- myseries_train %>%
  model(SNAIVE(Turnover))

d. Check the residuals. Do the residuals appear to be uncorrelated and normally distributed?

fit %>% gg_tsresiduals() 
## Warning: Removed 12 rows containing missing values (`geom_line()`).
## Warning: Removed 12 rows containing missing values (`geom_point()`).
## Warning: Removed 12 rows containing non-finite values (`stat_bin()`).

Comment

The mean of the residuals is not close to zero and there is significant correlations in the residuals series. The time plot of residuals shows that the variation of the residuals does not stay around the same across historical data after 2000 and therefore the residual variance may not be constant. The histogram suggests that the residuals may not be normal because the left tail seems a little too long. In sum, the forecasts and prediction intervals from this method may be inaccurate.

e. Produce forecasts for the test data.

forecast <- fit %>%
  forecast(new_data = anti_join(myseries, myseries_train))
## Joining, by = c("State", "Industry", "Series ID", "Month", "Turnover")
forecast %>% autoplot(myseries)

f. Compare the accuracy of your forecasts against the actual values.

fit %>% accuracy()

g. How sensitive are the accuracy measures to the amount of training data used?

Accuracy measures are sensitive to the size of training data used in the model. With a larger proportion of training data, the accuracy will increase. However, we should still use cross validation or other similar techniques to avoid the overfitting problem and to make the model more robust.

8.8 Exercises – Problem 7

Find an ETS model for the Gas data from aus_production and forecast the next few years. Why is multiplicative seasonality necessary here? Experiment with making the trend damped. Does it improve the forecasts?

# plot the data
aus_production <- aus_production 

aus_production %>%
  autoplot(Gas)

# fit the multiple ETS models
fit_gas <- aus_production %>%
  model(
    add = ETS(Gas ~ error("A") + trend("A") + season("N")),
    mult = ETS(Gas ~ error("M") + trend("A") + season("N")),
    add_with_sea = ETS(Gas ~ error("M") + trend("A") + season("A")), 
    mult_with_sea = ETS(Gas ~ error("M") + trend("A") + season("M")),
    mult_with_sea_damp = ETS(Gas ~ error("M") + trend("Ad") + season("M"))
    )
I
## function (x) 
## {
##     class(x) <- unique.default(c("AsIs", oldClass(x)))
##     x
## }
## <bytecode: 0x7fdafea68e68>
## <environment: namespace:base>
# make an forecast for five years
forecast_gas <- fit_gas %>% 
  forecast(h = 20) 

# plot the forecast
forecast_gas %>%
  autoplot(aus_production, level = NULL) %>%
  labs(title = "Gas Production in Australia")
## [[1]]

## 
## $title
## [1] "Gas Production in Australia"
## 
## attr(,"class")
## [1] "labels"

Comment

Multiplicative seasonality is necessary because multiplicative method is preferred when the seasonal variations are changing proportional to the level of the series. From the initial time plot and the time plot of forecasts, the seasonal nature of the time series increases proportional rather than remain the same.

I used 5 different ETS models and found that the forecast without seasonality is not fairly accurate. After considering the proportional changes above, I compare the multiplicative seasonality forecast with or without dampening. A small improvement is visible with the forecast having dampening.

9.11 Exercises – Problem 2

A classic example of a non-stationary series are stock prices. Plot the daily closing prices for Amazon stock (contained in gafa_stock), along with the ACF and PACF. Explain how each plot shows that the series is non-stationary and should be differenced.

# plot the data
amzn_stock <- gafa_stock %>%
  filter(Symbol == "AMZN")

amzn_stock %>%
  gg_tsdisplay(Close, plot_type = "partial")
## Warning: Provided data has an irregular interval, results should be treated with caution. Computing ACF by observation.
## Provided data has an irregular interval, results should be treated with caution. Computing ACF by observation.

  labs(title = "Amazon Closing Stock Price")
## $title
## [1] "Amazon Closing Stock Price"
## 
## attr(,"class")
## [1] "labels"

Comment

From the time plot of stock price, the time series seems to have an increasing trend, which makes it non-stationary. The ACF plot shows a slightly decreasing pattern and has \(lag_1\) with the largest and positive value, whereas all the lags are far beyond the ACF boundaries, which means that the data is not distributed as white noise and is not stationary. As for PACF plot, the large initial spike also indicates that the data is not stationary, so it should be difference to make it stationary.

Consider the number of Snowshoe Hare furs traded by the Hudson Bay Company between 1845 and 1935 (data set pelt).

a. Produce a time plot of the time series.

pelt <- pelt

# plot the data
pelt %>%

b. Assume you decide to fit the following model:

\(y_t\) = \(c\) + \(\phi_1\)\(y_{t-1}\) + \(\phi_2\)\(y_{t-2}\) + \(\phi_3\)\(y_{t-3}\) + \(\phi_4\)\(y_{t-4}\) + \(\varepsilon_t\) where \(\varepsilon_t\) is a white noise series.

What sort of ARIMA model is this (i.e., what are p, d, and q)?

fit_pelt <- pelt %>%
  model(ARIMA(Hare)) %>%
  report(fit_pelt)

d. The last five values of the series are given below:

The number of hare pelts is 19520 in 1931, 82110 in 1932, 89760 in 1933, 81660 in 1934 and 15760 in 1935.
The estimated parameters are \(c\) = 30993, \(\phi_1\) = 0.82, \(\phi_2\) = -0.29, \(\phi_3\) = -0.01, and \(\phi_4\) = -0.22.

Without using the forecast(), calculate forecasts for the next three years (1936 - 1939).

c = 30993
phi1 = 0.82
phi2 = -0.29
phi3 = -0.01
phi4 = -0.22

hares1931 = 19520
hares1932 = 82110
hares1933 = 89760
hares1934 = 81660
hares1935 = 15760

# calculate forecasts
hares1936 = c + phi1 * hares1935 + phi2 * hares1934 + phi3 * hares1933 + phi4 * hares1932
hares1937 = c + phi1 * hares1936 + phi2 * hares1935 + phi3 * hares1934 + phi4 * hares1933
hares1938 = c + phi1 * hares1937 + phi2 * hares1936 + phi3 * hares1935 + phi4 * hares1934

print(paste("The forecasts for the next 3 years (1936 - 1939) are", hares1936, ",", hares1937, ",", hares1938, "respectively."))
## [1] "The forecasts for the next 3 years (1936 - 1939) are 1273 , 6902.66 , 18161.2112 respectively."

e. Now fit the model in R and obtain the forecasts using forecast(). How are they different from yours? Why?

fit_pelt %>%
  forecast(h = 3)
## # A fable: 3 x 4 [1Y]
## # Key:     .model [1]
##   .model       Year              Hare  .mean
##   <chr>       <dbl>            <dist>  <dbl>
## 1 ARIMA(Hare)  1936  N(6634, 5.8e+08)  6634.
## 2 ARIMA(Hare)  1937 N(12878, 9.6e+08) 12878.
## 3 ARIMA(Hare)  1938 N(27999, 1.1e+09) 27999.

Comment

The forecasts obtained using the forecast() function are different from the ones we calculated manually. The reason for the differences is that the forecast() function uses a more sophisticated method to estimate the model parameters and forecasts. In addition, the forecast() function takes into account the uncertainty in the parameter estimates and the error term, which are not captured in the manual calculations. Therefore, the values calculated by the forecast() function should be more reliable.
